Adjust racks to top and middle positions and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Dice @potatoes{12%ounce} into ½-inch pieces. Trim, peel, and cut @carrots{12%ounce} on a diagonal into ½-inch-thick pieces. Strip @thyme{¼%ounce} leaves from stems; chop leaves until you have 2 tsp (4 tsp for 4 servings). Halve, peel, and finely chop @shallot{1}.

== Roasted Carrots & Thyme Potatoes ==

Toss potatoes on one side of a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @olive oil{1%tablespoon}, half the chopped thyme, and a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Toss carrots on empty side with a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%teaspoon}, salt, and pepper.

Roast on top rack, tossing halfway through, until tender and crisp, ~{20-25%minutes}.

While veggies roast, pat pork dry with #paper towels{}; season all over with salt and pepper.

== Pork ==

Heat a drizzle of olive oil in a large pan over medium heat. Add @chicken cutlets{10%ounce} and sear, turning occasionally, until browned all over, ~{4-8%minutes} (it'll finish cooking in the next step).

Transfer to a second baking sheet. Reserve pan.

> Swap in chicken or beef for pork. Cook chicken until cooked through, 3-5 minutes per side, or cook beef to desired doneness, 4-7 minutes per side.

Roast pork on middle rack until cooked through, ~{10-12%minutes}.

Transfer pork to a #cutting board{} to rest. Thinly slice pork crosswise.

> Skip this step for chicken or beef!

== Sauce ==

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of olive oil in pan used for pork over medium heat. Add shallot and remaining chopped thyme. Cook, stirring, until softened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Stir in @chicken stock concentrate{1}, @balsamic vinegar{5%teaspoon}, @fig jam{1}, and @water{¼%cup} (½ cup for 4 servings). Simmer until thick and saucy, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Remove pan from heat and stir in @butter{1%tablespoon} (2 TBSP for 4) until melted. Season with salt and pepper.

> Use pan used for chicken or beef here.

== To Serve ==

Divide potatoes, carrots, and pork between plates. Drizzle pan sauce over pork and serve.

> Thinly slice chicken or beef against the grain.

> Chicken is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.